04592nam a22009255i 9780520933699DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20072007cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2021696938  a97805209336997 a10.1525/97805209336992doi  a(DE-B1597)519315  a(OCoLC)558876160  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aML195 4aML195b.B47 2007 7aMUS0060002bisacsh04a780.903a780.9033  aLP 380202rvk1 aBerger, Karol, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBach's Cycle, Mozart's Arrow :bAn Essay on the Origins of Musical Modernity /cKarol Berger. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2007] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (444 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tIntroduction -- tPrelude: L’Orfeo, or the Anxiety of the Moderns -- tPart I. Bach’s Cycle -- tPart II. Mozart’s Arrow -- tPostlude: Between Utopia and Melancholy -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this erudite and elegantly composed argument, Karol Berger uses the works of Monteverdi, Bach, Mozart, and Beethoven to support two groundbreaking claims: first, that it was only in the later eighteenth century that music began to take the flow of time from the past to the future seriously; second, that this change in the structure of musical time was an aspect of a larger transformation in the way educated Europeans began to imagine and think about time with the onset of modernity, a part of a shift from the premodern Christian outlook to the modern post-Christian worldview. Until this historical moment, as Berger illustrates in his analysis of Bach's St. Matthew Passion, music was simply "in time." Its successive events unfolded one after another, but the distinction between past and future, earlier and later, was not central to the way the music was experienced and understood. But after the shift, as he finds in looking at Mozart's Don Giovanni, the experience of linear time is transformed into music's essential subject matter; the cycle of time unbends and becomes an arrow. Berger complements these musical case studies with a rich survey of the philosophical, theological, and literary trends influencing artists during this period.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aMusicy18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Classical.2bisacsh  a18th century.  aacademic.  aargument.  aartist.  aartistic trends.  aartistic.  abach.  abeethoven.  acase studies.  achristian.  achristianity.  aclassical composers.  aclassical music.  acomposers.  adon giovanni.  ahistorical.  ainstrumental music.  aliterary.  amonteverdi.  amozart.  amusic composers.  amusical composition.  aphilosophical.  aphilosophy.  apost christian.  apremodern.  ascholarly.  ast matthew passion.  atheology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052025091840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093369940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520933699423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520933699/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY